      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im studying for my physics midterm and im kinda stuck on entanglement. can u give me a quick summary of what quantum entanglement actually is? also how is it different from just regular classical correlation? thx",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon where two or more particles become so deeply connected that the state of one instantly influences the state of the other, no matter how far apart they are. It's like having two magical, invisible threads connecting two distant, enchanted goblins. If one goblin dances, the other one dances too, even if they're on opposite sides of the world. This connection is stronger than any regular classical correlation, where things just happen to be related but don't have that instant, magical link. In classical correlation, it's like two goblins who always wear matching hats because they were given them on the same day, but they don't dance together unless someone tells them to. Quantum entanglement is like having a secret, magical dance routine that only the goblins know, and they just follow it without any outside prompting.",
